Question 1 – Cardio Vascular Disease in England


The code below performs the following analyses as required:

  • Identify which of the given factors (overweight, smokers, wellbeing and poverty) has the strongest influence on the prevalence of CVD

  • Graphical visualisation of the effect of poverty upon CVD


Data dictionary


The data used for the following analyses originates from various datasets from the UK Office for National Statistics. Each row in the dataset represents one local authority region within the UK and displays the percentage of people who have recently suffered from cardiovascular disease (CVD) in that area.


The dataset variables are described in the following table:

Variable Description
area_name Name of the local authority region
area_code Unique identifier code for the local authority region
Population Total population living in the local authority region
Poverty Proportion (%) of people in the area who meet the definition of living in poverty
CVD Proportion (%) of people in the area who have recently experienced cardiovascular disease (CVD)
overweight Proportion (%) of people in the area who are classified as overweight
smokers Proportion (%) of people in the area who smoke
wellbeing Average wellbeing score of people living in the area

Analysis


Exploring the Individual Effects of Predictor Variables on the Target Variable

First, we aim to briefly examine the individual relationships between the predictor variables and the target variable with a correlation matrix and visualisations through scatterplots. This will help to identify their potential individual relationships and their strength. Subsequently, we will analyse the joint effects of the predictor variables by performing a multiple linear regression.


Correlation Matrix (Pearson):

# Calculate the Correlation Matrix
corr_matrix <- rcorr(as.matrix(cvd_data[, c("CVD", "Poverty", "overweight", "smokers", "wellbeing")]), type = "pearson") # As rcorr doesn't work very well with tibbles and data frames we input a matrix

# Correlation Matrix Visualisation

# Extract the correlation values
cor_matrix <- corr_matrix$r

# Rename the variables in the correlation matrix
colnames(cor_matrix) <- c("CVD", "Poverty", "Overweight", "Smokers", "Wellbeing")
rownames(cor_matrix) <- c("CVD", "Poverty", "Overweight", "Smokers", "Wellbeing")

# Extract the p-values
p_matrix <- corr_matrix$P
p_matrix_round <- round(p_matrix, 4)

# Visualise the correlation matrix with ggcorrplot
ggcorrplot(cor_matrix, 
           method = "square",
           type = "lower",  
           lab = TRUE,       
           p.mat = p_matrix,  
           insig = "blank")



The correlation matrix above shows all pairwise correlations of the variables.

  • It can be observed that there is a slight positive correlation between the predictor variables overweight-proportion, smoker-proportion and wellbeing-score with the target variable CVD-proportion, whereas the predictor variable poverty-proportion shows a slight negative correlation with the target variable CVD-proportion.
  • The strongest correlation between a variable and the CVD-proportion was found for the overweight-proportion (\(r = 0.32\)), followed by the poverty-proportion (\(r = -0.25\)) and wellbeing score (\(r = 0.25\)). The weakest correlation was found between smokers proportion and CVD-proportion (\(r = 0.18\)). Note: By squaring the \(r-value\) we get the proportion of variance explained e.g. \(0.32^2 = 0.10\), which means that about 10% of the variance can be explained by overweight.
  • All correlations between the predictor variables poverty, overweight, smokers, wellbeing and the target variable CVD are statistically significant as shown below (poverty: \(p-value < 0.0001\), overweight: \(p-value < 0.0001\), smokers: \(p-value = 0.0019\), wellbeing: \(p-value < 0.0001\)). Note: This would align with the coefficient significance of individual linear regressions e.g. CVD ~ overweight.

Exploring the Joint Effects of Predictor Variables on the Target Variable

So far we have only considered individual effects (variables independent of each other). We now change this by estimating a multiple regression model. First we will run the model with the unmodified data (easy to interpret), then we will fit the multiple regression model with the standardised data to better compare the coefficients.


Multiple Regression Model with unmodified data:

m.cvd.multiple <- lm(CVD ~ Poverty + overweight + smokers + wellbeing, data = cvd_data)
summary(m.cvd.multiple)

The multiple regression shows the following effects upon CVD-proportion (when controlling for the other variables):

  • Significant negative effect of poverty-proportion upon CVD-proportion (\(t(298)=-5.234\), \(p<0.0001\)), with every 1% increase in Poverty-proportion predicting an average decrease of 0.1840% in CVD-proportion (\(CI = [-0.2532, -0.1148]\)).
  • Significant positive effect of overweight-proportion upon CVD-proportion (\(t(298)=5.174\), \(p<0.0001\)), with every 1% increase in overweight-proportion predicting an average increase of 0.1099% in CVD-proportion (\(CI = [0.0681, 0.1516]\)).
  • Significant positive effect of smokers-proportion upon CVD-proportion (\(t(298)=3.574\), \(p=0.0004\)), with every 1% increase in smokers-proportion predicting an average increase of 0.1203% in CVD-proportion (\(CI = [0.0541, 0.1866]\)).
  • Significant positive effect of wellbeing-score upon CVD-proportion (\(t(298)=3.667\), \(p=0.0003\)), with every 1 point increase in wellbeing-score predicting an average increase of 1.8003% in CVD-proportion (\(CI = [0.8341, 2.7664]\)).


Before moving forward, we would like to briefly assess the linear relationship in our multiple linear regression model. To do this, we will create a residual plot to check for randomness and additionally plot the distribution of the residuals, which should be approximately normally distributed.

# Extract fitted values and residuals
fitted_values <- fitted(m.cvd.multiple)
residuals_values <- residuals(m.cvd.multiple)

# Create a data frame
residuals_df <- data.frame(Fitted = fitted_values, Residuals = residuals_values)

# Create the ggplot
resid_plot <- ggplot(residuals_df, aes(x = Fitted, y = Residuals)) +
              geom_point(color = "steelblue", size = 2, alpha = 0.7) +
              geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "black") +
              geom_smooth(method = "loess", color = "grey", se = FALSE, linetype = "solid", size = 1) +
              labs(title = "Residuals vs. Fitted Values",
                   x = "Fitted Values", y = "Residuals") +
              theme_minimal()

# Create a histogram of residuals
resid_histogram <- ggplot(data.frame(residuals_values)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = residuals_values), fill = "steelblue", bins = 20, colour = "black") +
  labs(x = "Residuals", y = "Frequency", title = "Histogram of Residuals") +
  theme_minimal()

grid.arrange(resid_plot, resid_histogram, nrow = 2)


We observe no obvious patterns in the residual plot, and the residuals appear to be fairly normally distributed, which suggests a linear relationship.


Note: It is important to note that the variables in this analysis are measured on different scales. For example, wellbeing is measured as a score ranging from 1 to 10, whereas the other variables are proportions expressed on a 0-100 scale. Using the raw values allows for straightforward interpretations, such as: an increase of 1% in the smoker-proportion leads to an increase of 0.1203% in the CVD-proportion. However, to compare the coefficients across variables more effectively, we will use the standardised data in the next step.


Multiple Regression Model with standardised data:

# Creating a dataset with standardised values
cvd_data_standardised <- cvd_data %>%
  mutate(
    CVD = scale(CVD),
    Poverty = scale(Poverty),
    overweight = scale(overweight),
    smokers = scale(smokers),
    wellbeing = scale(wellbeing))

# Run the multiple regression model with standardised values
m.cvd.multiple.stand <- lm(CVD ~ Poverty + overweight + smokers + wellbeing, data = cvd_data_standardised)
summary(m.cvd.multiple.stand)

The multiple regression with standardised data gives us the following information:

  • All predictors are still highly significant (same p-values as multiple regression with unmodified data).
  • In comparison to the correlation analysis (which examines individual relationships between the predictor and target variables), there is a slight shift in effects: Poverty now appears to have the strongest effect (-0.2952), while overweight remains very important (0.2840). Smokers (0.2091) and wellbeing (0.1969) follow, with slightly less weight.
  • The differences in results compared to the individual effects (gathered from the correlation analysis) can be explained by the dependencies between the variables. For example, wellbeing may depend on poverty, as shown by their negative correlation in the Pearson Correlation Matrix (\(r-value = -0.35\)). The higher the level of poverty, the lower the wellbeing score.


Due to these possible dependencies between the predictor variables, such as the negative correlation between poverty and wellbeing, it is necessary to check for multicollinearity. To do this, we calculate the Variance Inflation Factor scores (VIFs) to identify strong collinearity in our regression model, which could make the results unreliable.

# Check for multicollinearity
vif(m.cvd.multiple)
##    Poverty overweight    smokers  wellbeing 
##   1.263094   1.196546   1.359206   1.145506

The output shows that there is no severe data-based multicollinearity (All scores are clearly below the cut-off point of 5). Therefore, we do not need to undertake any corrections (e.g. exclusion of a predictor variables).


Visualising the Impact of Poverty on Cardiovascular Disease (CVD)

As requested by the task, we will provide visualisations below which illustrate the impact of poverty on cardiovascular disease (CVD).


As it is not entirely clear from the task whether the pure relationship between poverty and CVD should be plotted or whether the adjusted effect of poverty on CVD (via a prediction output of the multiple regression model) should be visualised, both methods will be presented below.


Raw relationship between Poverty and CVD:

ggplot(cvd_data, aes(x = Poverty, y = CVD)) +

The plot shows the relationship between poverty-proportion (%) and CVD-proportion (%). A weak negative correlation is indicated by the black line (Pearson-Correlation-Coefficent: \(r=-0.25\)), where higher poverty levels are associated with slightly lower CVD-proportions. A potential reason for this (which would require further research) could be differences in access to healthcare and check-ups.


Adjusted effect of poverty on CVD (via a prediction output of the multiple regression model):

# Create a new data frame for the prediction
cvd_prediction_data <- data.frame(
  Poverty = seq(min(cvd_data$Poverty), max(cvd_data$Poverty), length.out = 100),  
  overweight = mean(cvd_data$overweight, na.rm = TRUE),                          
  smokers = mean(cvd_data$smokers, na.rm = TRUE),                                
  wellbeing = mean(cvd_data$wellbeing, na.rm = TRUE))
  # Creates a data frame with 100 rows. The average values for overweight, smokers, and wellbeing are calculated and kept constant. For poverty, 100 equally distributed values are generated, ranging from the minimum to the maximum value in the current (real) data frame.

# Predict values based on the model
cvd_prediction_data$predicted_CVD <- predict(m.cvd.multiple, newdata = cvd_prediction_data)

# Plot the adjusted effect of Poverty on CVD
ggplot(cvd_prediction_data, aes(x = Poverty, y = predicted_CVD)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1) +
  labs(title = "Adjusted Effect of Poverty on CVD (all other variables kept at their average)",
       x = "Poverty-Proportion (%)",
       y = "Predicted CVD-Proportion (%)") +
  theme_minimal()


The plot shows the effect of poverty while keeping all other variables (overweight, smokers, wellbeing) constant at their average value (calculated from the actual dataset). Once again, we observe the negative trend in the relationship.


Conclusion

We examined the predictor variables overweight, smokers, wellbeing and poverty, both individually (using a correlation matrix and scatter plots) and while accounting for interdependencies (via multiple regression). Across all analyses, all coefficients were highly significant and contributed to the model’s explanatory power. Overweight consistently stood out as a very influential factor in both the correlation analysis and multiple regression. Poverty also emerged as a key factor, showing a particularly strong influence in the multiple regression model. The other two variables wellbeing and smokers, were both significant as well but had a comparatively slightly weaker effect (in the multiple regression). Furthermore, we assessed multicollinearity, which did not substantially impact the analysis, as only weak collinearity was detected.


Addition Information:

Further research: It would be particularly interesting to investigate why poverty seems to have a strong negative effect on the CVD proportion. Possible explanations (not proven) could include a lack of access to healthcare services for people from poorer backgrounds, fewer check-ups compared to others or other factors that might be found.

Interaction effects: Although we have not tested interaction terms in this analysis, it is possible to formulate new hypotheses to explore interactions (e.g. is the effect of being overweight on CVD the same across different levels of smoker proportions?). Testing interaction terms randomly and only keeping the ones with significant results can lead to p-hacking, which may cause overfitting and unreliable conclusions. Since testing interactions is not required for this task, we will not include them in this analysis.

Exploring the Joint Effects of Predictor Variables on the Target Variable

So far we have only considered individual effects (variables independent of each other). We now change this by estimating a multiple regression model. Since we previously found that new_range does not seem to provide much explanatory power for predicting customer.satisfaction on its own, we will now examine whether this also holds true in our multiple regression model. To do this, we will first run the model with the three predictor variables (staff.satisfaction, delivery.time, SES_category), and then add new_range to compare whether the performance of the more complex model is significantly better. Afterwards, we will run and interpret the selected model.


Multiple Regression Model - Model comparison:

# Multiple Regression model without new_range
m.cs.multiple <- lm(customer.satisfaction ~ staff.satisfaction + delivery.time + SES_category, data = cust_satisfaction)

# Multiple Regression model with new_range
m.cs.multiple_more_complex <- lm(customer.satisfaction ~ staff.satisfaction + delivery.time + SES_category + new_range, data = cust_satisfaction)

# Model comparison
anova(m.cs.multiple, m.cs.multiple_more_complex)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: customer.satisfaction ~ staff.satisfaction + delivery.time + 
##     SES_category
## Model 2: customer.satisfaction ~ staff.satisfaction + delivery.time + 
##     SES_category + new_range
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F Pr(>F)
## 1    295 276.52                           
## 2    294 275.86  1   0.65631 0.6995 0.4036

The second model adds no significant improvement in comparison to the first model (\(F(1,294)=0.6995, p = 0.4036\)).

Conclusion: In further analyses, we will focus on the model with the three variables: staff.satisfaction, delivery.time and SES_category.

Before moving forward, we would like to briefly assess the linear relationship in our multiple linear regression model. To do this, we will create a residual plot to check for randomness and additionally plot the distribution of the residuals, which should be approximately normally distributed.

# Extract fitted values and residuals
fitted_values2 <- fitted(m.cs.multiple)
residuals_values2 <- residuals(m.cs.multiple)

# Create a data frame
residuals_df2 <- data.frame(Fitted = fitted_values2, Residuals = residuals_values2)

# Create the ggplot
resid_plot2 <- ggplot(residuals_df2, aes(x = Fitted, y = Residuals)) +
               geom_point(color = "steelblue", size = 2, alpha = 0.7) +
               geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "black") +
               geom_smooth(method = "loess", color = "grey", se = FALSE, linetype = "solid", size = 1) +
               labs(title = "Residuals vs. Fitted Values",
                    x = "Fitted Values", y = "Residuals") +
               theme_minimal()

# Create a histogram of residuals
resid_histogram2 <- ggplot(data.frame(residuals_values2)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = residuals_values2), fill = "steelblue", bins = 20, colour = "black") +
  labs(x = "Residuals", y = "Frequency", title = "Histogram of Residuals") +
  theme_minimal()

grid.arrange(resid_plot2, resid_histogram2, nrow = 2)


We observe no obvious patterns in the residual plot, and the residuals appear to be fairly normally distributed, which suggests a linear relationship.


Note: It must once again be noted that the variables are interpreted differently. We have both continuous and factor-variables. Also the ranges from the continuous variables are different e.g. staff satisfaction (probably) from 1-10 and delivery time with bigger values. Therefore for example, a +1 change in the staff satisfaction score has to be reviewed differently than a +1 change in delivery time.


Due to these possible dependencies between the predictor variables, it is necessary to check for multicollinearity. To do this, we calculate the Variance Inflation Factor scores (VIFs) to identify strong collinearity in our regression model, which could make the results unreliable.

# Check for multicollinearity
vif(m.cs.multiple)
##                        GVIF Df GVIF^(1/(2*Df))
## staff.satisfaction 1.273317  1        1.128414
## delivery.time      1.039410  1        1.019515
## SES_category       1.317221  2        1.071309

The output shows that there is no severe data-based multicollinearity (All scores are clearly below the cut-off point of 5). Therefore, we do not need to undertake any correction (e.g. exclusion of a predictor variable).


Company Analysis Request: Effect of Delivery Times on Customer Satisfaction and Interaction Effect with SES Store Sizes

Conclusion

The analysis resulted in a number of important findings, which are listed below:

  • The differences between stores with and without new range products were not statistically significant. As a result, this variable was excluded from further analysis.
  • The variable staff.satisfaction was strongly positively correlated with customer satisfaction, while delivery time showed a negative correlation. Furthermore, both variables were statistically significant in explaining and predicting customer satisfaction scores, with staff satisfaction demonstrating slightly stronger explanatory power, as indicated by the standardised coefficient.
  • The SES-category variable added explanatory and predictive power, showing significant differences between all category pairs (especially low - medium and medium - high, but also low - high) in our analysis.
  • Through a VIF test, we concluded that there is no evidence of data-based multicollinearity among our variables. Therefore, it was not necessary to make any corrections, such as excluding predictor variables.
  • An interaction term between delivery time and SES-category revealed a significant effect, particularly for High SES-stores compared to the reference level Low. The analysis showed that delivery time had a stronger negative effect on customer satisfaction for High SES-stores compared to the reference category Low SES-stores. For medium SES-stores, changes in delivery time did not have a significantly stronger effect on customer satisfaction compared to Low SES-stores. These results were consistent both with and without controlling for staff satisfaction as covariate.
